def: A shaking, trembling, or concussion of the earth, due tosubterranean causes, often accompanied by a rumbling noise. The waveof shock sometimes traverses half a hemisphere, destroying cities andmany thousand lives; -- called also earthdin, earthquave, andearthshock. Earthquake alarm, a bell signal constructed to operate onthe theory that a few seconds before the occurrence of an earthquakethe magnet temporarily loses its power.
Among Mohammedans, a warrior champion or veteran, esp. in thedestruction of infidels.
One of the teeth in the forepart of the mouth; an incisor.
Becoming to a Christian.A virtuous and a Christianlike conclusion. Shak.
Begin in or at peace; tranquil; quiet; free from, or notdisposed to, war, disorder, or excitement; not quarrelsome.-- Peace"a*ble*ness, n.-- Peace"a*bly, adv.
In the way of executing or performing.
That with which one makes shift; a temporary expedient. JamesMill.I am not a model clergyman, only a decent makeshift. G. Eliot.
A broad ice sheet resting on a plain or plateau and spreadingoutward from a central névé, or region of accumulation.
